ay” practices continue reading the main story advertisement continue reading the main story “if you knew and paid the right people you could do business in new york” mr cuomo said “hundreds of millions of dollars in taxpayer money went to people who were politically connected that’s not going to be allowed any more”for two years mr cuomo has been conducting an investigation into the millions of dollars and other favors that friends relatives and aides of the former state comptroller alan g hevesi gained for helping steer business to mr hevesi while he was the sole trustee of the state’s  billion pension fund since then the investigation has widened to include pension funds in other statesmr cuomo said that his investigation was only in the “fourth inning” and that “new developments will be coming down the road” mr hevesi has not been charged but charges have been brought against six people who did business with himas for carlyleriverstone the cuomo investigation looked into payments made by riverstone and mr leuschen to a number of politically connected intermediaries as the carlyleriverstone joint venture sought — and obtained —  million in business from the new york state pension fund between  and before making these payments according to the attorney general carlyleriverstone had only limited success in obtaining business from the new york state pension fund but the joint venture’s fortunes changed after the payments were madein a statement michael freitag a riverstone spokesman said “for our investors and the firm we believe we have reached the right decision through this resolution” photo andrew cuomo the new york attorney general said his investigation was in the fourth inning credit chester higgins jrthe new york times david snow executive editor at private equity international a research firm said that the  million settlement was a wise course of action by riverstone advertisement continue reading the main story “if your choice is paying a  million fine or doing a perp walk it is money well spent” mr snow said he added however that should charges be brought against mr leuschen it could have serious consequences for the riverstone funds because limited partners might want to pull their money out“leuschen is a key man and if he is removed from the firm that will be big trouble for the franchise” mr snow added newsletter sign up continue reading the main story please verify youre not a robot by clicking the box invalid email address please reenter you must select a newsletter to subscribe to sign up you agree to receive occasional updates and special offers for the new york timess products and services thank you for subscribing an error has occurred please try again later you are already subscribed to this email view all new york times newsletters see sample manage email preferences not you privacy policy opt out or contact us anytime carlyleriverstone funds were founded in  when mr leuschen an oil and energy specialist at goldman sachs at the time teamed up with carlyle to invest in the energy sector over the years the joint venture raised billions of dollars from state pension fundsriverstone now has  billion in assets under management while carlyle is the world’s secondlargest private equity firm with assets of nearly  billionriverstone paid  million more than carlyle which a person in the attorney general’s office said reflected that riverstone — and not carlyle — was the focus of the activities that mr cuomo was trying to root outthe person who asked not to be identified because the investigation was still in progress said that the  million payment was equal to the amount of fees that riverstone gained from the pension fund the new york state common retirement fundthe cuomo investigation looked into several types of payments between riverstone and a number of wellplaced political intermediariesmr leuschen made a personal investment of  in a lowbudget movie named “chooch” that was produced by the brother of a state official david j loglisci mr loglisci the former chief investment officer of the new york state pension fund has since been indicted on corruptionrelated fraud chargesin addition riverstone paid  million in fees to an influential placement agent hank morris who also has been chargedanother person receiving the placement fees barrett wissman is a former business partner of mr leuschen and a neighbor of his in montana where the two men have adjoining ranches advertisement continue reading the main story mr wissman who has since pleaded guilty and paid a  million fine first alerted mr leuschen to the fact that the new york state pension fund might be interested in making investments in the energy sector continue reading the main story we’re interested in your feedback on this page tell us what you think whats next loading go to home page » site index the new york times david leuschen  professional profile linkedin main content starts below david leuschenpresidentmanaging partnerlocationrichmond virginiaindustryfinancial servicescurrentretirement  estate investment servicespreviousanderson  strudwick branch cabell scott  stringfelloweducationvirginia commonwealth universitywebsitesreis websitereis facebook connectionsview david’s full profile its freeyour colleagues classmates and  million other professionals are on linkedinview david’s full profilesummaryas president of retirement  estate investment services which is affiliated with commonwealth financial network the largest privately owned brokerdealer david offers  years experience in the financial services industry his practice focuses on helping people manage and invest their retirement accounts and other family assets  doing so at a fair and reasonable price he employs prudent and proven tax and asset management strategies he helps clients with iras and rollover accounts as well as complicated employee retirement benefits and stock option plans for those clients who wish to leave assets to their heirs he offers es